rnment faced the domestic and international challenges of the postwar world. This study draws on a wide range of primary sources and will appeal to those interested in modern Irish and British history and in the Second World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zNorthern Ireland. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aDevolved government.  aEconomic mobilisation.  aIrish Republican Army.  aMilitary conscription.  aSecond World War.  aSocial policy.  aUlster unionism.1 aOllerenshaw, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611163040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526111630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526111630/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles